## Game Master Guidance

### Balancing Availability

Control crafting power through material availability:

**Common Components:** Readily available in cities, enable basic crafting
**Rare Components:** Require quests or defeating powerful creatures
**Legendary Materials:** Unique items from major story arcs

Don't let players craft everything they want immediately. Scarcity creates quests and limits power escalation.

### Setting Crafting Standards

Define your campaign's crafting accessibility:

**High Magic:** Crafting common, materials available, many NPCs craft
**Standard Magic:** Crafting available to dedicated characters, materials require effort
**Low Magic:** Crafting rare, materials scarce, most items found not crafted

Communicate standards early so players can plan character builds accordingly.

### Crafting as Plot Hooks

Use crafting requirements to generate adventures:

**Material Quests:** "The +2 armor requires mithril from deep dwarf mines—are you willing to negotiate with them?"
**Time Pressure:** "The warlord attacks in 3 days. Can you finish that weapon in time?"
**Rival Crafters:** "Another artificer wants the same phoenix feather. Who claims it?"

Crafting shouldn't be pure bookkeeping—make it drive story.

### Handling Unique Items

Players will request custom items not in standard lists:

**Encourage Creativity:** Work with players to design balanced unique effects
**Set Appropriate Costs:** Match Flow/time/gold to comparable standard items
**Require Narrative Justification:** Unique properties need in-world explanation

If player wants "Bow that recalls arrows," that's reasonable utility (similar to returning weapon property). Price accordingly and require quest for self-retrieving material.

### Failed Crafting

Decide whether crafting can fail:

**Automatic Success (Recommended):** Time and Flow investment guarantee success—failure wastes player resources unsatisfyingly
**Risk-Based Crafting:** Crafting requires check, failure loses materials but refunds Flow
**Critical Failure:** Rare catastrophic failures create cursed items or explosions

Most campaigns use automatic success—players investing weeks and 10 Flow deserve functional results. Reserve failure chance for experimental legendary crafting.

